here's an example: In BW, towards the end you go through the entire Mason initiation ritual.
The ritual consists of the to-be members travelling to the Temple of Solomon. On the way they go through a hall with a checkered floor are stopped and harassed by 3 evil men (killers of the architect of Solomon's Temple) and fend them off to reach the temple.
Towards the end of BW you go through the 3 ruffians (the ninja guys) and then pass through 2 immense pillars to enter the temple where N is waiting. Behind N is the 3rd pillar, which symbolizes Solomon.
Team Plasma itself has 7 sages, like Emperor Justinian and his own sages were 7.
Ghetsis' staff is almost exactly the symbol for Christ used in that era, the "Chi Rho" an X and a P meaning Christ in greek, the actual logo of team plasma is exactly that symbol.
Hell, there's a lab in BW2 that is literally named P2, which is a literal and direct reference to the Italian masonic division "P2" or "Propaganda 2".

these are all in because templars and masons were some of the groups that fervently believed in and practiced alchemy
not going to write a book about it in a post, but the other games also depict other groups and alchemical practices, especially SV and SM

com:
Ok, level with me here.
SV are unfinished. They have mediocre graphics that get horrifyingly bad at any considerable distance, and it STILL runs like crap. This is pathetic and in itself is enough to warrant deeming the final product outright bad. I don’t deny this.
BUT, am I crazy or is this the only real issue with SV?
Im one of those people who’s been upset with the direction this series was going for over a decade now. We often pin it on gen 6 but the truth is the issues that made gen 6+ bad were problems that had been building since very early on. GF just seemed comfortable continuously shitting out unambitious, barebones games, with PAINFUL amounts of handholding. The whole reason I loved Pokémon to begin with was because I loved the escapism of going on adventure across a vast region with my mons, but the series was very consistently moving farther and farther away from that for several generations. I had every reason to think these issues would only get worse, so yea I was a bit of a doomer.

But then SV came out and all at once fixed every single problem I had, while leaning heavily into the stuff I actually liked and wanted out of the series. You gotta understand, for me this was a huge game changer. All these issues I thought I’d have to cope with forever, just GONE. Replaced with one giant glaring issue that arguably ruins the games in a much more objective way, but consider; now that the issues are objective and are moreso just lack of polish rather than fundamental issues with the design, it’s WAY more likely that they’ll be fixed. Especially since even normies are shitting on them for it. We’re not homefree yet but truth is this absolutely FEELS like it’s the mythic return-to-form that I’ve been waiting for. I’m genuinely sorry for the people who are still doomposting, not because they’re wrong, but because I’m finally free the heavy burden of doomerism myself. Just hang tight guys, sooner or later we’ll all be free.

These and more are all concrete truths, and critics have every right to rip on them given what we know what Nintendo and even the other parts of TPC are capable of.

Conceptually speaking though, I believe the direction SV represents is bright. Regarding NPCs, the characterization, development, and interrelations displayed in SV is the most advanced in the entire Pokémon game franchise. Although the story is fundamentally contrived and requires serious suspension of disbelief at times, it is still compelling and at times even surprising (to the point where there is even a war between two competing theories about the direction of the plot). The non-overworld maps are very intricately detailed: Academy classrooms, Area Zero and labs, named NPC homes, and the major cities are lovingly crafted, faceted with tiny details and easter eggs that appear as though someone genuinely enjoyed their job. All of this was intentional, even if not all of it could be capitalized upon, if it was poorly executed at times, or if some details were definitive "misses" rather than "hits" with large groups of players, and that's a good sign.
